\b What is Test Environments Management\b0 ?\par
Wikipedia describes it like this: Test Environment Management (TEM) is a function in the software delivery process that aids the software testing cycle by providing valid, stable, and usable test environments to execute test scenarios or replicate bugs.\par
\b\fs28 To take this one step further, we'd describe it as follows:\b0\fs32\par
Test Environment Management is the function of understanding your Test Environments* and applying that knowledge, with appropriate governance and services to ensure that each testing environment is available for IT Projects, the DevTest community, and the overall software development lifecycle.\par
\b Common Testing Environments\b0\par
*IT & Test Environments, that may include:\par
\b Development Environments, for development.\b0\par
Tip: It is not uncommon for developers to have their Testing Environment on their operating system. However, later phases of testing generally benefit from people sharing the testing environment.\par
\par
System Testing Environments, for isolated system tests.\par
Integration Testing Environments, to check connectivity.\par
User Acceptance Test Environment, for business sign-off.\par
Performance Testing Environment, for performance tests.\par
Tip: The Performance Testing Environment is often the most expensive test environment due to its need for extra resources to accommodate Performance Tests like Stress, Volume & Load Testing.\par
\par
Security Testing Environment, for pen-testing.\par
Staging Environment, a test bed for a final walkthrough &\par
Production Environment\par
